      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I recently completed a 4 day juice fast without using a juicer and I wanted to share how I did it.</p>
<p>No, I didn&#8217;t use one of the pricey fresh juice delivery services out there. It costs about $300 (including shipping)  for a three day juice cleanse using providers like Blueprint Cleanse or Liv Juice!</p>
<p>I used store bought juice and did this fast on the cheap &#8211; and in this post, I&#8217;m going to show you how I did it.</p>
<p>My main goal for thefast was more weight loss centered, but &#8220;cleansing&#8221; my body of toxins is still an added side benefit.</p>
<h3>Detoxification and Checking Ingredients</h3>
<p><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-2255" title="Store Bought Juices" src="http://www.juicecleansenow.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/photo-300x300.jpg" alt="Doing a Juice Fast With Store Bought Juice" width="300" height="300" />To ensure you get &#8220;cleansing&#8221; benefits from your juicing, it&#8217;s IMPERATIVE that you only use juices that are 100% pure. You don&#8217;t want juices with any kind of additives. You want clean, 100% natural juice. You will need to read labels.</p>
<p>For example, I&#8217;ve got a bottle of Sambazon Acai juice, which claims &#8220;Contains 100% Juice.&#8221; But when you read the ingredients, it also contains &#8220;Organic Agave Syrup.&#8221; Well, to me, if it&#8217;s got sugar (even by way of agave) in it, that&#8217;s not 100% juice, that&#8217;s juice + sugar. In my book, it doesn&#8217;t qualify for a juice *cleanse* &#8211; with cleanse being the imperative word here.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve also got a bottle of Barsotti Twisted Berry juice &#8211; it claims &#8220;100% Juice &amp; Puree.&#8221; Reading the ingredients, it actually contains only fruit and veggie juice, just like you want. No added sugars &#8211; so that&#8217;s good news.</p>
<p>But&#8230; It&#8217;s not organic.</p>
<p>The thing is though, that &#8220;Organic&#8221; doesn&#8217;t necessarily mean what we think it does. <a href="http://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~lhom/organictext.html">Organic does not mean pesticide and chemical free</a>. And <a href="http://agriculturesociety.com/politics-and-food/whole-foods-et-al-grant-blessing-of-gmo-alfalfa-to-monsanto/">the future of &#8220;Organic&#8221; is troubled</a>, to say the least.</p>
<p>Listen, the best thing for a cleanse would be local, small farmed, pesticide and chemical free juice.</p>
<p>But you&#8217;re here, and you&#8217;re looking for a way to do it with store bought juice, so we have to make some compromises.</p>
<p>For me, the priority is to just be drinking the juice and nothing but the juice while on a  juice cleanse.</p>
<p>For you, the priority might be the go all organic and get rid of as many toxins as you can muster, even if it means a little agave nectar gets thrown into the mix.</p>
<p>Whatever your priority is, pick one. It&#8217;ll help guide you when you go to the store.</p>
<p>Juicing purists will tell you that using store bought juices and smoothies, which are pasteurized, is not as good as using fresh juice. It makes sense. But doing a juice cleanse with pasteurized juice is better than no juice cleanse at all! Dont let purists discourage you &#8211; what you are doing is GOOD!</p>
<h3>Shopping for Your Juice Fast</h3>
<p>I modeled my store bought juice fast after the fancy delivery juice cleanses like LivJuice. So I wanted some lemonade, for it&#8217;s liver detoxifying benefits, some green juice, because that&#8217;s where all the good stuff is hidden, a nut milk for protein and various other juice blends for flavor.</p>
<p>Be very, very careful when shopping for your juices!</p>
<p>Most juices your find on the shelves are juice from concentrate, contain extra sugars and preservatives and other crap you don&#8217;t want while cleansing.</p>
<h4>Green Juices</h4>
<p><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-2259" title="Screen Shot 2012-02-16 at 2.18.28 PM" src="http://www.juicecleansenow.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/Screen-Shot-2012-02-16-at-2.18.28-PM-110x300.png" alt="Doing a Juice Fast With Store Bought Juice" width="110" height="300" />I had a tough time because I don&#8217;t really like a straight green juice, but I wanted to get some of it every day. Fruit juice, cashew milk and lemonade is nice, but without the greens, it&#8217;s not so much a fast as a fruit juice orgy.</p>
<p>I chose Columbia Gorge Organic Pure Pressed &#8220;Just Greens&#8221; because it actually contained ONLY greens with no fruit to sweeten it up.</p>
<p>Products like Naked Juice&#8217;s Green Machine and Odwalla&#8217;s Superfood are green in color but are mostly comprised of fruit juices and purees. The amount of greens they use it more a token nod, not an actual significant contributor to the drink.</p>
<p>You&#8217;ll have to pick what&#8217;s available at your local market, with an eye for the biggest concentration of greens possible.</p>
<p>Turns out, I thought the stuff was AWFUL so I ended up mixing it in with Odwalla Superfood for taste. Not what I&#8217;d intended, but a solution to still get some down if you&#8217;re like me and the thought of drinking a cucumber doesn&#8217;t appeal.</p>
<h4>Fruit Juices</h4>
<p>For my general fruit juice blends, I stuck with Odwalla Superfood and Naked&#8217;s Green Machine because they do contain some vegetables, even though you can&#8217;t taste them.</p>
<p><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-2262" title="Odwalla-Original-Superfood" src="http://www.juicecleansenow.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/Odwalla-Original-Superfood-300x173.jpg" alt="Doing a Juice Fast With Store Bought Juice" width="300" height="173" />But I found that the fruit blends were so high in calories they weren&#8217;t really what I wanted for weight loss. Plus, since they&#8217;re a smoothie product, they&#8217;re pretty thick.</p>
<p>I ended up mixing each one with water on a 1:1 ratio &#8211; one part water, one part juice. This cut down on the calories and made it a bit more palatable as the days wore on.</p>
<p>I kept a few other juices on hand to add variety &#8211; cranberry, pomegranate, carrot, etc.</p>
<h4>Proteins</h4>
<p>I stayed away from soy based protein, which meant that both Odwalla and Naked brand protein juices were out. No particular reason except that I&#8217;ve read a lot of bad things about over consumptions of soy and that the pre-made cleanses I was modeling used nut milks instead.</p>
<p>I made a batch of cashew milk, but it&#8217;s really not cost effective so I quickly switched to 100% almond milk, no flavors or sweeteners.</p>
<h3>Sample Store Bought Juice Fast Menu Plan</h3>
<p>It&#8217;s a cleanse, after all, so you&#8217;ll want to be drinking plenty of water in addition to your juices. Herbal tea is also allowed on a juice fast, but steer clear of caffeinated varieties &#8211; and coffee.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s a beginner, new to juicing menu plan:</p>
<p><strong>Wake: </strong>Hot water with lemon</p>
<p><strong>Breakfast: </strong>Green juice</p>
<p><strong>Mid-morning: </strong>Fruit blend</p>
<p><strong>Lunch: </strong>Green Juice</p>
<p><strong>Afternoon: </strong>Lemonade</p>
<p><strong>Dinner: </strong>Fruit blend</p>
<p><strong>Evening: </strong>Nut milk</p>
<p>More experienced juicers can sub out any of the fruit juices (except the lemonade) for green juices to make a more cleanse-ier, lower calorie fast.</p>
<p>This is the menu plan I followed and I found that after Day 1, I really tired of the sweetness of juice. I wanted something savory. I succumbed to homemade tomato soup &#8211; not exactly perfect, but 100% tomatoes, vegetable stock and basil, so not too far off plan either.</p>
<p>Those of you with a better tolerance for green juices likely won&#8217;t have the same problem &#8211; the sweetness overload &#8211; as you&#8217;ll have juices to choose from that aren&#8217;t sweet.</p>
<p>Not having a juice isn&#8217;t an excuse not to juice fast anymore!</p>
<p>If you&#8217;ve done a store-bought juice fast or are planning one, let me know your tips and tricks in the comments!</p>
